[2] Cholera - Nigeria [Bauchi state]
Date: Tue 6 Mar 2018
Source: Leadership [edited]
https://leadership.ng/2018/03/06/cholera-outbreak-kills-2-bauchi/


A total of 2 people have died and 18 others hospitalized following a cholera outbreak in Bauchi state metropolis. This was disclosed by the chairman of Bauchi State Primary Healthcare Agency, Pharmacist Ibrahim Gamawa while briefing newsmen yesterday [Mon 5 Mar 2018] at the Emergency Operation Centre Bauchi. Gamawa stated that out of the 20 new cases, 2 died at the Abubakar Tafawa Balewa University Teaching Hospital (ATBUTH) and the remaining 18 patients are responding to treatment in the same hospital.

He revealed that the 20 cases came from 4 different locations within Bauchi metropolis; Danmar A and B Isangaya school, Hardo within Kobi ward, Makama B at Nasarawa Jahun and Makama A Gwallaga. The Chairman said that his agency has adequate drugs like ORS [oral rehydration solution], chlorine for disinfection etc. that will aid the public in fighting the outbreak. He added that his agency had set things in motion to disinfect areas in the state.

Gamawa then called on the people of the state to cultivate good personal hygiene and also practice the habit of keeping their environment clean and they should always cover their food items properly, adding that by doing that, it would stop the disease from spreading further. He said that a sensitisation campaign in the media and other channels was being carried to sensitize people on the disease and how to avoid it.

[Byline: Beatrice Gondyi]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Bauchi, usually referred to as Bauchi State to distinguish it from the city of Bauchi, is a state in northern Nigeria. Its capital is the city of Bauchi. The state was formed in 1976 when the former North-Eastern State was broken up. It originally included the area now in Gombe State, which became a distinct state in 1996. The area can be found on a map at: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bauchi_State. - Mod.LL]

