[3] Cholera - Malawi
Date: Wed 7 Mar 2018
Source: Capital Radio Malawi [edited]
http://www.capitalradiomalawi.com/index.php/blog/local-news/capital-news/item/9087-cholera-death-toll-at-20


The death toll for the cholera outbreak in Malawi continues to rise, with the number increasing to 20 from 17 within 2 days. National figures further indicate that 722 people are receiving medical treatment, rising from 693 reported on [Sun 4 Mar 2018]. This is despite health authorities declaring that 8 districts are cholera free.

The worst hit districts are Lilongwe and Karonga which have a similar death toll of 7 each. The latest deaths have been recorded in Salima and Dedza district, which was earlier put on the cholera free list.

Poor access to safe drinking water and sanitation are being described as the major causes of cholera. Spokesperson for the Ministry of Heath Joshua Malango earlier told Capital FM on government's interventions to contain the further spread of the disease.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The country of Malawi, officially the Republic of Malawi, is a landlocked country in south east Africa that was formerly known as Nyasaland. It is bordered by Zambia to the north west, Tanzania to the north east, and Mozambique on the east, south and west. It can be seen on a map at http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/malawi.pdf. A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be seen at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5672462,176. - Mod.LL]

