[6] Cholera - Angola (Cabinda province)
Date: Wed 7 Mar 2018
Source: Noticias AO Minuto [in Portuguese, machine trans., edited]
https://www.noticiasaominuto.com/mundo/968897/confirmados-casos-de-colera-no-enclave-angolano-de-cabinda


According to Health provincial secretary in Cabinda, Maria Carlota Tati, samples of 3 suspected cases [of cholera] were sent to laboratories in Luanda, capital of Angola, and the tests confirmed the presence of _Vibrio cholera_. The official, quoted today by the Angolan news agency, Angop, said that there are 13 cases reported, of which a death occurred in a private health unit.

Maria Carlota Tati considers the situation controlled, noting that the cases are confined to 3 districts of the city of Cabinda. The 1st suspected case was registered on [20 Feb 2018], at the Provincial Hospital of Cabinda. As immediate measures, she added that surveillance teams are disinfecting cacimbas and distributing free tablets for the treatment of drinking water, as well as educating and sensitizing residents about cholera prevention measures.

Cabinda thus becomes the 2nd province to face cases of cholera in Angola, after the Uíge, affected since 2017 by the disease, with more than a dozen dead in more than 600 cases, since December 2017.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Cabinda (also spelled Kabinda, formerly called Portuguese Congo), is an exclave and province of Angola, a status that has been disputed by several political organizations in the territory. The capital city is also called Cabinda. The province is divided into 4 municipalities; Belize, Buco-Zau, Cabinda and Cacongo.

Cabinda is separated from the rest of Angola by a narrow strip of territory belonging to the Democratic Republic of the Congo, which bounds the province on the south and the east. Cabinda is bounded on the north by the Republic of the Congo, and on the west by the Atlantic Ocean.

It can be seen on a map at: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cabinda_Province. - Mod.LL]
